---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "CAGR Calculator",
  description: "Stop guessing your actual return. This Compound Annual Growth Rate calculator reveals exactly how fast your investments are growing over time.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does CAGR mean?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "CAGR stands for Compound Annual Growth Rate. It represents the constant rate at which an investment would have grown if it had compounded at the same rate every year."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How is CAGR different from average annual return?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Average annual return just takes the arithmetic mean of returns over several years, which ignores the effect of compounding. CAGR accounts for compounding, providing a much more accurate picture of actual growth."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a good CAGR?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A 'good' CAGR depends on the context and the risk involved. For context, the historical average annual return of the S&P 500 is around 10% before inflation."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can CAGR be negative?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. If the ending value of an investment is lower than the beginning value, the CAGR will be negative, indicating an annualized loss over that period."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "When should I not use CAGR?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "CAGR is not ideal if you are making regular deposits or withdrawals during the investment period. In those cases, the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is a more accurate measure."
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Mastering the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR)",
    "description": "Understand how to calculate and interpret the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) to evaluate your investment performance accurately.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SiliconBased"
    }
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/cagr-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>CAGR Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Calculate the Compound Annual Growth Rate of your investments</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="calc-grid">
        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="initial">Beginning Value ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="initial" min="0.01" step="any" value="10000" placeholder="e.g. 10000">
          <div id="initial-error" class="error-msg" style="display: none;">Beginning value must be greater than 0.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="final">Ending Value ($)</label>
          <input type="number" id="final" min="0" step="any" value="15000" placeholder="e.g. 15000">
          <div id="final-error" class="error-msg" style="display: none;">Please enter a valid ending value.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="years">Number of Years</label>
          <input type="number" id="years" min="0.1" step="any" value="5" placeholder="e.g. 5">
          <div id="years-error" class="error-msg" style="display: none;">Years must be greater than 0.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="result-card">
        <h3>Compound Annual Growth Rate</h3>
        <div class="result-value" id="cagr-result">8.45%</div>

        <div class="result-details">
          <div class="detail-row">
            <span>Total Growth:</span>
            <span id="total-growth" class="highlight">50.00%</span>
          </div>
          <div class="detail-row">
            <span>Absolute Profit/Loss:</span>
            <span id="absolute-profit" class="highlight">+$5,000.00</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>Understanding Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR)</h2>
      <p>The Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) is one of the most useful and widely used metrics in finance to evaluate the performance of an investment over time. It provides a smoothed, annualized rate of return that shows what an investment yielded on average per year, assuming the profits were reinvested at the end of each year.</p>

      <p>Unlike absolute return (which just tells you the total percentage gained or lost) or average annual return (which can be misleading due to volatility), CAGR gives you a clear, easily comparable single number.</p>

      <h3>The Flaw in "Average Annual Return"</h3>
      <p>To understand why CAGR is important, consider a simple example. Imagine you invest $1,000. In Year 1, your investment drops by 50% to $500. In Year 2, it grows by 100% back to $1,000.</p>
      <p>If you calculate the simple arithmetic average of those returns: (-50% + 100%) / 2 = <strong>25% Average Annual Return</strong>.</p>
      <p>Looking at that 25% average, you might think you made money. However, your ending balance is exactly the same as your starting balance ($1,000). Your actual growth is 0%. The CAGR correctly calculates this as exactly <strong>0%</strong>, revealing the true performance.</p>

      <h3>The CAGR Formula</h3>
      <p>Calculating CAGR manually requires a bit of math, specifically finding an exponent root:</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <strong>CAGR = [(EV / BV)<sup>(1/n)</sup>] - 1</strong>
      </div>
      <p>Where:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>EV</strong> = Ending Value (the final amount)</li>
        <li><strong>BV</strong> = Beginning Value (the initial investment)</li>
        <li><strong>n</strong> = Number of years</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Let's use the default values in our calculator as an example:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>EV</strong> = $15,000</li>
        <li><strong>BV</strong> = $10,000</li>
        <li><strong>n</strong> = 5 years</li>
      </ul>
      <p>CAGR = [(15000 / 10000)<sup>(1/5)</sup>] - 1</p>
      <p>CAGR = [(1.5)<sup>0.2</sup>] - 1</p>
      <p>CAGR = [1.08447...] - 1 = 0.08447... or roughly <strong>8.45%</strong></p>

      <h3>When to Use CAGR</h3>
      <p>CAGR is excellent for comparing the historical performance of different investments over similar time horizons. For example, if you want to compare how a specific mutual fund performed against the S&P 500 or against a fixed-rate <a href="/cd-interest-calculator">Certificate of Deposit (CD)</a> over a 10-year period, CAGR is the best metric to use.</p>

      <h3>Limitations of CAGR</h3>
      <p>While powerful, CAGR has a few notable limitations that investors should be aware of:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>It ignores volatility:</strong> CAGR assumes a smooth, steady growth rate every year. It completely masks the "bumpy ride" the investment took to get there. Two investments could have the exact same CAGR over 5 years, but one might have grown steadily by 8% a year, while the other swung wildly from +40% to -20%.</li>
        <li><strong>It doesn't account for ongoing contributions:</strong> The standard CAGR formula assumes a single initial lump sum investment that is left alone. If you are regularly adding money to an account (like dollar-cost averaging into a 401(k)), CAGR will give you an inaccurate picture of your return. In those cases, you should use the Internal Rate of Return (IRR).</li>
        <li><strong>It is purely historical:</strong> A high historical CAGR does not guarantee future performance. It simply tells you what happened in the past.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What does CAGR mean?</summary>
        <p>CAGR stands for Compound Annual Growth Rate. It represents the constant rate at which an investment would have grown if it had compounded at the same rate every year.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is CAGR different from average annual return?</summary>
        <p>Average annual return just takes the arithmetic mean of returns over several years, which ignores the effect of compounding. CAGR accounts for compounding, providing a much more accurate picture of actual growth.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a good CAGR?</summary>
        <p>A "good" CAGR depends on the context and the risk involved. For context, the historical average annual return of the S&P 500 is around 10% before inflation.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can CAGR be negative?</summary>
        <p>Yes. If the ending value of an investment is lower than the beginning value, the CAGR will be negative, indicating an annualized loss over that period.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>When should I not use CAGR?</summary>
        <p>CAGR is not ideal if you are making regular deposits or withdrawals during the investment period. In those cases, the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is a more accurate measure.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const initialInput = document.getElementById('initial');
      const finalInput = document.getElementById('final');
      const yearsInput = document.getElementById('years');

      const initialError = document.getElementById('initial-error');
      const finalError = document.getElementById('final-error');
      const yearsError = document.getElementById('years-error');

      const cagrResultEl = document.getElementById('cagr-result');
      const totalGrowthEl = document.getElementById('total-growth');
      const absoluteProfitEl = document.getElementById('absolute-profit');

      function formatCurrency(value) {
        return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
          style: 'currency',
          currency: 'USD',
          minimumFractionDigits: 2,
          maximumFractionDigits: 2
        }).format(Math.abs(value));
      }

      function calculateCAGR() {
        let hasError = false;

        const initial = parseFloat(initialInput.value);
        if (isNaN(initial) || initial <= 0) {
          initialError.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        } else {
          initialError.style.display = 'none';
        }

        const final = parseFloat(finalInput.value);
        if (isNaN(final) || final < 0) {
          finalError.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        } else {
          finalError.style.display = 'none';
        }

        const years = parseFloat(yearsInput.value);
        if (isNaN(years) || years <= 0) {
          yearsError.style.display = 'block';
          hasError = true;
        } else {
          yearsError.style.display = 'none';
        }

        if (hasError) {
          cagrResultEl.textContent = '---';
          totalGrowthEl.textContent = '---';
          absoluteProfitEl.textContent = '---';
          totalGrowthEl.className = '';
          absoluteProfitEl.className = '';
          cagrResultEl.style.color = 'var(--text-primary)';
          return;
        }

        // CAGR = (EV/BV)^(1/n) - 1
        const cagr = (Math.pow(final / initial, 1 / years) - 1) * 100;

        const absoluteProfit = final - initial;
        const totalGrowthPercent = (absoluteProfit / initial) * 100;

        // Formatting
        const isNegative = cagr < 0;
        const colorClass = isNegative ? 'negative' : 'positive';
        const sign = isNegative ? '-' : '+';
        const profitSign = absoluteProfit < 0 ? '-' : '+';

        cagrResultEl.textContent = cagr.toFixed(2) + '%';
        cagrResultEl.style.color = isNegative ? '#ef4444' : 'var(--accent-color)';

        totalGrowthEl.textContent = sign + Math.abs(totalGrowthPercent).toFixed(2) + '%';
        totalGrowthEl.className = isNegative ? 'negative' : 'positive highlight';

        absoluteProfitEl.textContent = profitSign + formatCurrency(absoluteProfit);
        absoluteProfitEl.className = isNegative ? 'negative' : 'positive highlight';
      }

      // Add event listeners
      const inputs = [initialInput, finalInput, yearsInput];
      inputs.forEach(input => {
        input.addEventListener('input', calculateCAGR);
        input.addEventListener('change', calculateCAGR);
      });

      // Initial calculation
      calculateCAGR();
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }

    .calc-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }

    .input-group { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.5rem; }
    .input-group label { font-weight: 600; font-size: 0.95rem; }

    input { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }

    .error-msg { color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.25rem; }

    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .result-card h3 { margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; word-break: break-all; transition: color 0.3s; }

    .result-details { border-top: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); padding-top: 1.5rem; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.75rem; text-align: left; }
    .detail-row { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; font-size: 1.05rem; }
    .detail-row span:first-child { color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .detail-row span:last-child { font-weight: 600; }

    .highlight.positive { color: #10b981 !important; }
    .negative { color: #ef4444 !important; }

    .explainer { line-height: 1.7; margin: 3rem 0; }
    .explainer h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin: 2rem 0 1rem; }
    .explainer h3 { font-size: 1.4rem; margin: 1.5rem 0 0.75rem; }
    .explainer p { margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer ul { margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .explainer li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .formula-box { background: var(--card-bg); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; margin: 1rem 0; font-size: 1.2rem; }
    .explainer a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .explainer a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .faq-section { margin-top: 3rem; }
    .faq-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1.25rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1.1rem; list-style-position: inside; }
    .faq-section details p { margin-top: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
